1970) is an American politician who has been a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from {{ushr|IN|4}} since 2011. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he served two terms as [[Secretary of State of Indiana]] from 2002 to 2010. When Rokita was elected to office in 2002 at age 32, he became the youngest [[Secretary of State (U.S. state government)|secretary of state]] in the [[United States]] at the time.\n\nRokita was a candidate to replace [[Mike Pence]] in the [[Indiana gubernatorial election, 2016|2016 Indiana gubernatorial election]] after Pence withdrew from the race to be [[Donald Trump]]'s running mate in the [[United States Presidential election, 2016|2016 U.S. Presidential election]]. He lost to [[Eric Holcomb]], Pence's lieutenant governor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/us/indiana-governor-mike-pence.html|title=Indiana Governor Mike Pence|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2017, Rokita announced he would vacate his House seat to run for the Indiana U.S. Senate seat held by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Joe Donnelly]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2017/08/08/rep-todd-rokita-embraces-trump-he-launches-indiana-senate-bid/550882001/|title=Rep. Todd Rokita embraces Trump as he launches Indiana Senate bid|work=Indianapolis Star|access-date=2017-08-13}}</ref> On May 8, 2018, he lost the Republican primary election to [[Mike Braun]] by a little more than 11%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2018-election/primaries|title=2018 Election Results, News, Candidates & Polls|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Education and personal life==\nRokita grew up in [[Munster, Indiana]] and attended [[Munster High School]].<ref name=\"Franklin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/lake/munster/munster-speech-team-takes-top-state-honors-for-lucky-th/article_f446a3fe-f6ab-5890-8d6d-6f7cf23c53eb.html|title=Munster speech team takes top state honors for lucky 13th time|date=May 17, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2014|author=Franklin, Lu Ann}}</ref> He holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Wabash College]] in [[Crawfordsville, Indiana]], where he was an [[Eli Lilly and Company|Eli Lilly]] Fellow and a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblinks.sigmachi.org/preview/marketing/PAC/list.pdf|format=PDF |title=Sigma Chi Candidates for the U.S. Congress 2010|website=Weblinks.sigmachi.org|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> He has a law degree from [[IUPUI]]'s [[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=R000592 |title=ROKITA, Todd \u2013 Biographical Information |publisher=Bioguide.congress.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>[[File:Congressman Rokita's Family.jpg|left|thumb|Congressman Rokita with his wife Kathy and their two children]]\nRokita was a practicing attorney. In 1997 he joined the secretary of state's office as general counsel. He later became deputy secretary of state.<ref name=\"vote-in.org\">{{cite web|url=http://vote-in.org/Intro.aspx?State=IN&Id=INRokitaTodd|title=Vote In biographical profile of Todd Rokita|publisher=Vote-in.org|accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Rokita served as legal counsel for seven Florida counties during the [[2000 United States presidential election recount in Florida|recount]] for the [[George W. Bush presidential campaign, 2000|George W. Bush presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toddrokita.com/experience.asp|title=Todd Rokita for Indiana Secretary of State|date=2002-10-13|access-date=2018-05-29|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021013075025/http://www.toddrokita.com/experience.asp|archivedate=2002-10-13|df=}}</ref>\n\nRokita is a member of the Director's Circle of the Indiana Council for Economic Education, the state bar association, the Knights of Columbus, and the National Rifle Association. He has also served as Chair of NASS's New Millennium Young Voters Summit of 2004, chair of the standing Voter Participation Committee and vice chair of the Securities Regulation Committee.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://rokita.house.gov/about-me/full-biography|title=Congressman Todd Rokita biodata|date=2012-01-27|publisher=Rokita.house.gov|accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\nRokita formerly lived in [[Clermont, Indiana|Clermont]], an \"included town\" in [[Indianapolis]] under the [[Unigov]] system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historycms.house.gov/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=15032389214|title=OFFICIAL LIST OF MEMBERS|website=Historycms.house.gov|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> The 2010 round of redistricting cut out the 4th's share of Indianapolis and [[Marion County, Indiana|Marion County]], leaving Rokita's home 500 yards outside the new 4th's eastern border. Members of Congress are required to live only in the state they represent, but it is a strong convention that they live within their district's borders. In 2012 Rokita ran for reelection from his home in Clermont,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/article_21e1600b-ede7-54cf-989d-0fc4a139bd4e.html|title=Remap leaves U.S. Rep. Rokita outside his district|last=Carden|first=Dan|date=May 15, 2011|accessdate=May 21, 2011|work=[[The Times of Northwest Indiana|The Times]]}}</ref> but he later bought a home near [[Brownsburg, Indiana|Brownsburg]], a western suburb of Indianapolis within the 4th district.<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n===Advocacy work===\nRokita's oldest son, Teddy, suffers from [[Angelman syndrome]]. Rokita and his wife, Kathy, are active in promoting awareness of the syndrome.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wthr.com/article/local-family-opens-door-little-known-syndrome|title=Local family opens the door on little-known syndrome|website=Wthr.com|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> They participate in and organize charity walks related to Angelman. He has cited his son's ailment in policy speeches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4467126%2Frep-todd-rokitaangelman-syndrome|title=Archived copy|accessdate=2016-10-05|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006042617/https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4467126%2Frep-todd-rokitaangelman-syndrome|archivedate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\nA commercial-rated pilot, Rokita volunteers his time by flying people in need of non-emergency medical care to hospitals and clinics throughout the Midwest for treatment with organizations that include Veterans Airlift Command and Angel Flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://generalaviationnews.com/2011/10/19/congress-is-listening-at-least-one-member-is|title=Congress is listening\u2026 at least one member is|date=2011-10-19|website=Generalaviationnews.com|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wndu.com/content/news/Indiana-congressman-flies-veteran-for-free-384957371.html|title=Indiana congressman flies veteran for free|website=Wndu.com|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bannergraphic.com/story/1969104.html|title=Local News: Congressman Rokita featured on Lincoln Day menu this Sunday|date=2013-05-15|website=Bannergraphic.com|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the Indiana chapter of the International Flying Farmers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyergroup.com/news/election-profiles/article_30a9d050-6398-11e4-a48c-27a2b2540a5f.html|title=Election Profiles|date=2014-11-03|website=Flyergroup.com|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Indiana Secretary of State==\nRokita was elected by his peers nationally to serve on the nine-member federal executive board of the Election Assistance Commission.<ref name=\"vote-in.org\"/> The commission is charged by law to address election reform issues on a nationwide basis. Rokita has testified about Indiana's voting reform efforts before the United States Congress. As secretary of state, he visited each of Indiana's 92 counties at least once per year. Rokita was named as one of the \"40 under 40\" by the ''Indianapolis Business Journal in 2005''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ibj.com/articles/16116-forty-under-40-recipients|title=Forty Under 40: Recipients|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> He was active in the [[National Association of Secretaries of State]] (NASS), and after serving as the elected treasurer, he became the President for the 2007\u201308 term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/newsitem.asp?ID=24474|title=Rokita Becomes President of National Association of Secretaries of State \u2013 Newsroom \u2013 Inside INdiana Business with Gerry Dick|publisher=Insideindianabusiness.com|date=2007-07-18|accessdate=2010-08-23|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229133237/http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/newsitem.asp?ID=24474|archivedate=2012-02-29|df=}}</ref>\n\nRokita was a named defendant when Indiana's voter identification case went before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] on January 9, 2008; the combined cases of ''[[Crawford v. Marion County Election Board]]'' (07-21) and ''[[Indiana Democratic Party v. Rokita]]'' (07-25) involved an Indiana law that requires voters display state-issued photo IDs. In April 2008, the Supreme Court upheld that law. Rokita also served as Indiana's chief [[securities fraud]] investigator.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nIn September 2009, Rokita outlined a plan to reform how Indiana's legislative districts are drawn to reduce [[gerrymandering]]. He proposed making it a felony for lawmakers to use political data or incumbents' addresses when drawing electoral maps. Rokita said boundaries should follow existing county and township lines, and that each of the 50 Senate districts should be divided into two House districts, claiming that would lead to more competitive legislative elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20090908/NEWS05/909080333/Lawmakers+draw+line+at+redistricting+plan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911075012/http://www.indystar.com/article/20090908/NEWS05/909080333/Lawmakers+draw+line+at+redistricting+plan|dead-url=yes|archive-date=September 11, 2009|title=Lawmakers draw a line at Rokita's redistricting plan|last=Schneider|first=Mary Beth|date=September 8, 2009|work=The Indianapolis Star|accessdate=2009-09-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Rokita signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any global warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Rokita_Todd.pdf|title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-13|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601132054/http://www.americansforprosperity.org/files/Rokita_Todd.pdf|archivedate=2012-06-01}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Tenure===\nRokita serves as vice-chairman of the [[United States House Committee on the Budget]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.toddrokita.com/issues|title=Issues|work=Todd Rokita for Congress|access-date=2017-06-06}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\n====Agriculture====\nHe co-sponsored the Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act \u2013 passing the House in March 2011 \u2013 in order to prevent the \"significant burden on small businesses for little obvious environmental benefit.\" Rokita also co-sponsored the Preserving America's Family Farms Act \u2013 which passed the House in July 2012 \u2013 citing Indiana's dependence on youth work on family farms.<ref name=\"toddrokitaforcongress1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toddrokitaforcongress.com/about.html|title=Todd Rokita for Congress|publisher=Todd Rokita for Congress|accessdate=2013-10-21|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012195736/http://www.toddrokitaforcongress.com/about.html|archivedate=2012-10-12|df=}}</ref>\n\n====Education====\nAs Chairman of the Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary, and Secondary Education, he had an active role in crafting the [[Every Student Succeeds Act]], which reauthorized the 1965 [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexis Moberger|url=http://wlfi.com/2016/03/13/new-education-law-guts-no-child-left-behind-act|title=New education law guts No Child Left Behind Act|website=Wlfi.com|date=2016-03-13|accessdate=2016-11-11|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109142131/http://wlfi.com/2016/03/13/new-education-law-guts-no-child-left-behind-act/|archivedate=2016-11-09|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Klein|first=Alyson|url=http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2015/11/_after_more_than_a.html|title=House, Senate ESEA Compromise Sails Through Conference Committee|website=Blogs.edweek.org|date=2015-11-19|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> In May, Rokita introduced bipartisan legislation to help students and parents with student loan debt. His legislation would allow student loan borrowers to refinance loans and have access to lower market rate loans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jconline.com/story/news/college/2017/05/27/rokita-introduces-bill-tackle-student-loans/102189828/|title=Rokita introduces bill to tackle student loans|work=Journal & Courier|access-date=2017-06-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Rokita and Senator [[Marco Rubio]] introduced the Education Opportunities Act, legislation to expand school choice options for low- and middle-income families to help them attend the school of their choice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rubio.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/press-releases?ID=4B118A3F-1689-475B-A98B-4E92A889FA0B|title=Rubio, Rokita Reintroduce Educational Opportunities Act|work=U.S. Senator for Florida, Marco Rubio|access-date=2017-07-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2017/03/tax_credit_school_choice_plan_congress_path.html?cmp=SOC-SHR-FB|title=Two Possible Paths for a Tax-Credit School Choice Plan in Congress|last=Andrew Ujifusa|website=Education Week - Politics K-12|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rokita.house.gov/press-release/release-rokita-rubio-reintroduce-educational-opportunities-act|title=ROKITA, RUBIO REINTRODUCE EDUCATIONAL OPPORTUNITIES ACT|website=rokita.house.gov|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2014, Rokita introduced the [[Strengthening Education through Research Act (H.R. 4366; 113th Congress)]].<ref name=\"4366allactions\">{{cite web|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4366/all-actions|title=H.R. 4366 \u2013 All Actions|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 6, 2014}}</ref> The bill would amend and [[authorization bill|reauthorize]] the [[Education Sciences Reform Act of 2002]] and would authorize the [[appropriations bill (United States)|appropriation]] of $615 million for fiscal year 2015 and $3.8 billion over the 2015\u201319 period to support federal educational research, statistical analysis, and other activities.<ref name=\"cbo4366\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45300|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4366|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=May 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Gun law====\nRokita voted in favor of a bill \"Requiring State Reciprocity for Carrying Concealed Firearms\" in November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/34167/todd-rokita/37/gun-issues|title=Todd Rokita's Voting Records on Issue|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n====Tax reform====\nIn 2017, Rokita voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=1|website=The New York Times|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nRokita previously served on the [[United States House Committee on House Administration|Committee on House Administration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/committee_info/scsoal.pdf|format=PDF|title=List of Standing Committees|website=In.gov|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cha.house.gov/press-release/house-administration-adopts-subcommittee-assignments|title=House Administration Adopts Subcommittee Assignments &#124; Committee on House Administration |website=Cha.house.gov|date=2011-01-25|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=August 2017}}\n;2002\n\nOn June 15, 2002, Rokita won the Republican nomination for Indiana Secretary of State at the state convention over [[Mike Delph]], then an aide to U.S. Representative [[Dan Burton]], Marion County Coroner John McGodd, and then-Vanderburgh County Commissioner [[Richard Mourdock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/uncategorized/gop-nominates-rokita-at-convention/article_8dc133f9-86e1-53af-bcfd-9951f21de5ab.html|title=GOP nominates Rokita at convention|website=Nwitimes.com|date=2002-06-15|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> Rokita went on to win the general election with 53.4% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/files/2002_ELECTION_BOOKLET.pdf|format=PDF|title=Election Results: Indiana: 2002|website=In.gov|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2006\n\nRokita received the Republican nomination again in 2006 and won the general election with 51.1% of the vote in a year when Democrats took five of Indiana's nine congressional seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/sos/elections/files/2006_Election_Report.pdf|format=PDF|title=Election Results: Indiana: 2006|website=In.gov|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Indiana, 2010#District 4}}\nOn February 1, 2010, three days after Congressman [[Steve Buyer]] of {{ushr|Indiana|4}} said that he would retire at the end of his term, Rokita posted an announcement on [[Facebook]] making clear his intentions to run for the open seat. Buyer's announcement touched off a free-for-all among area Republicans to succeed him. Ultimately, 13 candidates entered the Republican primary, including Rokita.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nWith a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+14, the 4th is one of the most Republican districts in the [[Eastern Time Zone]] and tied for the second-most Republican in the state (behind the 5th District). It was taken for granted that whoever won the primary would be heavily favored to be the district's next representative. Rokita won the primary with 42% of the vote and the general election with 68.6% of the vote.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n;2012\nRokita won the general election in 2012 with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/apps/sos/election/general/general2012?page=office&countyID=-1&officeID=5&districtID=-1&candidate=|title=Election Results: Indiana: 2012|website=In.gov|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2014\nRokita won the Republican nomination in 2014 with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/apps/sos/primary/sos_primary14?page=office&countyID=-1&partyID=-1&officeID=5&districtID=-1&districtshortviewID=-1&candidate=|title=Election Results: Indiana: 2014|website=In.gov|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> He won the general election with 67% of the vote over John Dale, a teacher at [[Western Boone High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/apps/sos/election/general/general2014?page=office&countyID=-1&officeID=5&districtID=-1&candidate=|title=Election Results: Indiana: 2014|website=In.gov|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2016\n\nRokita won the Republican nomination in 2016 with 60% of the vote. In the general election, he faced John Dale in a rematch from 2014. Rokita was reelected with 65% of the vote to Dale's 30%. Libertarian Steven M. Mayoras received 5%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/apps/sos/election/general/general2016?page=office&countyID=-1&officeID=5&districtID=-1&candidate=|title=Indiana General Election|website=[[Secretary of State of Indiana]]|accessdate=August 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n;2018\n\nOn August 8, 2017, Rokita announced his intention to run for the U.S. Senate in 2018 against Democratic incumbent [[Joe Donnelly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2017/08/08/us/politics/ap-us-indiana-senate-the-latest.html|title=The Latest: Rokita to Formally Announce Indiana Senate Bid|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=August 8, 2017}}</ref> He lost the Republican primary election to [[Mike Braun]], coming in second with 30% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2018-election/primaries|title=2018 Election Results, News, Candidates & Polls|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Domestic issues===\n====Education====\nRokita supports charter schools, school choice, and reducing the role of the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] in setting education policy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Klein |first=Alyson |url=http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2013/01/conservative_rep_todd_rokita_n.html|title=Conservative Rep. Todd Rokita Named Chairman of K-12 Panel|website=Blogs.edweek.org|date=2013-01-03|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n====Energy and oil====\nRokita believes \"in an all-of-the-above policy that utilizes all available resources and technologies, so long as such resources and technologies are supported by the free market.\"<ref name=\"Issues\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.toddrokita.com/issues|title=Issues|work=Todd Rokita for Congress|access-date=2017-07-14}}</ref>\n\n====Environment====\nRokita has a 4% lifetime voting rating from the [[League of Conservation Voters]], an environmentalist group. In 2016, the group gave him a 0% rating.<ref>[http://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/todd-rokita National Environmental Scorecard: Todd Rokita], League of Conservation Voters (last accessed April 8, 2016).</ref> He does not accept the [[scientific consensus on climate change|scientific consensus]] that [[Attribution of recent climate change|human activity is the driving factor]] of [[climate change]],<ref name=\"Wilkins\">Ron Wilkins, [http://www.jconline.com/story/news/local/2016/06/28/voters-ask-congressman-guns-climate/86452966/ Voters ask Rep. Todd Rokita about gun control, climate change], ''[[Lafayette Journal & Courier]]'' (June 28, 2016).</ref><ref name=\"MacNeal\">Caitlin MacNeal, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/26/todd-rokita-climate-change_n_3817215.html GOP Rep Todd Rokita: Connecting Climate Change To Humans Is 'Arrogant'], ''Huffington Post'' (August 26, 2013).</ref> and at a 2013 town-hall event called the idea that climate change was caused by human activity \"arrogant.\"<ref name=\"MacNeal\"/><ref>Kirsten Gibson, [http://www.purdueexponent.org/city_state/article_bd15b4a3-ce01-55b8-a972-27109a6eb44e.html Rokita holds town hall in Lebanon], ''Purdue Exponent'' (August 26, 2013).</ref>\n\n====Gun law====\nRokita has stated: \"I'm proud of my 'A' rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]]\" and has said that he will \"protect our [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|2nd Amendment right]] to keep and bear arms.\"<ref name=\"toddrokitaforcongress1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/37|title=Todd Rokita's Ratings and Endorsements - The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|date=2016-05-03|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n====Health care====\nRokita supports repealing [[ObamaCare|Obamacare]].<ref name=\"Issues\"/> He opposes health care regulations that increase the national debt, earning a \"B\" rating by the National Taxpayers Union 2011 Positions on Tax and Spending.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/interest-group/872/rating/5941|title=National Taxpayers Union Rating - The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n===Economic issues===\n====Agriculture====\nRokita opposes direct federal government regulation of agriculture. A representative of a heavy-farming district in [[Indiana]], he supports deregulating agriculture, earning him an \"A\" rating from the American Farm Bureau Federation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/4|title=Todd Rokita's Ratings and Endorsements - The Voter's Self Defense System |publisher=Vote Smart|date=2016-05-03|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n====National debt and federal spending====\nRokita has said, \"Unless we get our government spending under control, we will unfairly burden the next generation with massive amounts of debt. We need to reform these programs to solve the problem.\"<ref name=\"Issues\"/>\n\n===International issues===\n====Immigration and refugees====\nRokita supported President Trump's 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] temporarily banning citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries from entering the U.S.<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Whip Count: Here's where Republicans stand on Trump's controversial travel ban|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/29/heres-where-republicans-stand-on-president-trumps-controversial-travel-ban|newspaper=Washington Post|date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Rokita expressed concern that border agents could come in contact with illegal immigrants carrying the Ebola virus, saying, \"from a public-health standpoint\" it is important to know who is coming across the southern border, citing the [[Ebola virus epidemic]] spreading in Africa and news reports indicating that nationals from 75 different countries had been apprehended between 2010 and 2014 illegally crossing the Mexico-United States border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/93wibc/garrison8-4-final|title=Garrison8: 4 FINAL by 93WIBC|website=Soundcloud.com|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n===Social issues===\n====Abortion====\nRokita opposes abortion and has maintained a 100% pro-life voting record according to the [[National Right to Life Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Federal NRLC Scorecard - 115th Congress, Combined Sessions|url=http://www.capwiz.com/nrlc/scorecard.xc?chamber=H&state=US&session=115&x=10&y=10|publisher=National Right-to-Life Committee|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> He holds that \"every life is a precious gift from God that begins from the moment of conception.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toddrokita.com/issues|title=Issues|date=2016-08-30|accessdate=2017-09-01|5=|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20160830221204/http://www.toddrokita.com/issues|archivedate=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\n====Cannabis====\nRokita has a \"D\" rating from [[NORML]] for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related causes. He opposes veterans having access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Indiana Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/indiana|website=NORML|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Tribal lands====\nRokita authored the Tribal Labor Sovereignty Act. The bill would \"make clear that the [[National Labor Relations Board]] has no jurisdiction over businesses owned and operated by an Indian tribe and located on tribal land.\" It cleared the House as of 2018, but has not been considered in the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wong|first1=Scott|title=Five things lawmakers want attached to the $1 trillion funding bill|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/377682-five-things-lawmakers-want-attached-to-the-1-trillion-funding-bill|website=The Hill|accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\nAfter the [[Donald Trump Access Hollywood tape]] was released, Rokita said, \"Nothing has changed about my support for Donald Trump and Mike Pence.\"<ref name=\"Groppe111617\">{{cite web|last1=Groppe|first1=Maureen|title=Indiana Senate candidates trade jabs over sexual harassment claims against others|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/2017/11/16/indiana-senate-candidates-trade-jabs-over-sexual-harassment-claims-against-others/871446001|website=Indianapolis Star|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date || Position || Status || Opponent || Result || Vote share || Top-opponent vote share\n|-\n| 2002 || [[Secretary of State of Indiana]] || Open-seat || [[John Fernandez (Indiana politician)|John Fernandez]] (D) || Elected || 53.41%<ref>http://www.capitolandwashington.com/results/2002/20/1/</ref> || 42.46%\n|-\n| 2006 || [[Secretary of State of Indiana]] || [[